  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    What is UMA?&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Unified Method Architecture (UMA)&amp;nbsp;defines an approach for defining &quot;methods&quot; consisting of method content and&#xD;
    processes.&amp;nbsp;It defines a standard&amp;nbsp;way&amp;nbsp;to specify all aspects of a methodology (or method), namely:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Processes&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Activities and Tasks&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Work Products (deliverables)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Guidance&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Basic Principles&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    UMA is based&amp;nbsp;on the following fundamental&amp;nbsp;separations of concerns:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The separation of core method definitions versus the usage of it in processes&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The definition of adaptations of the method for different situations&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Packaging and configuration of method content, processes, and guidance in libraries&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A separation of recommended activities from associated guidance&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A separation of semantic elements from their notation and usage in process diagrams&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Basic Elements of UMA&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The most fundamental principle of the UMA is the separation of&amp;nbsp;reusable core method content (e.g., &lt;em>Tasks&lt;/em>&#xD;
    and &lt;em>Activities&lt;/em>) from its application in processes and almost all of UMA's elements are categorized along this&#xD;
    separation.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The UMA separates reusable core method content from its application in processes.&amp;nbsp; Method content describes what&#xD;
    is to be produced, the necessary skills required and the step-by-step explanation describing how specific development&#xD;
    goals are achieved, independently of the placement of these items within a development lifecycle.&amp;nbsp; Processes take&#xD;
    these method elements and relate them into semi-ordered sequences that are customized to specific types of projects.&#xD;
    For example, a software development project that develops an application from scratch performs development tasks such&#xD;
    as &quot;Develop Vision&quot; or &quot;Use Case Design&quot; similar to a project that extends an existing software system.&amp;nbsp; However,&#xD;
    the two projects will perform the Tasks at different points in time with a different emphasis, i.e. they will perform&#xD;
    the steps of these tasks at different point of time and perhaps apply individual variations and additions.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The figure below shows the difference between method content and process by representing them as two different&#xD;
    dimensions:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Method content describing how development work is being performed is categorized by disciplines.&amp;nbsp; Each&#xD;
        discipline is comprised of tasks (not visible in the figure) that provide step-by-step descriptions of how specific&#xD;
        development goals are achieved.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        For a process, tasks have been referenced by the process from the method content and placed into breakdown&#xD;
        structures and workflows ready for instantiation by allocating resources to perform the work and having real work&#xD;
        products as the inputs and outputs of the tasks.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;Diagram illustrating the separation of Method and Process content within the UMA Meta-Model&quot;&#xD;
    src=&quot;./resources/uma_hump.jpg&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p class=&quot;picturetext&quot; align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Method Content definition versus&lt;br />&#xD;
    the application of Method Content in a Process&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    UMA's key concepts reflect this separation of method content from process as shown in the figure below.&amp;nbsp; It show&#xD;
    that a Method (also referred to as a Method Framework) comprises on method content described with concepts such Work&#xD;
    Products, Roles, Task and Categories as well as Processes described with Activities, Capability Patterns, or Delivery&#xD;
    Processes.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
